PRD: OLAP Strategy for Reporting Queries

1. Overview

All reporting queries — balance sheet, income statement, trial balance, loan aging, portfolio analytics — run directly against the OLTP database. As transaction volume grows, these queries will increasingly compete with customer-facing operations for database resources. A 10-year-old cooperative with 50,000 members, 500,000 journal entries, and 10,000 active loans will find that the trial balance query takes seconds instead of milliseconds, locking tables and degrading member-facing operations.

The `docs/database_principles.md` (lines 706-721) prescribes a future OLAP strategy (ClickHouse or similar). This PRD defines the path: start with PostgreSQL materialized views today (zero new infrastructure), and design the query layer for future extraction to a dedicated OLAP system when volume demands it.

2. Goals

Isolate reporting queries from the OLTP write path

Provide fast, consistent report data without table locks or query contention

Design a reporting layer that can be extracted to a dedicated OLAP system (ClickHouse, PostgreSQL replica, or data warehouse) without rewriting application code

Deliver reports from data that is at most 15 minutes stale (near-real-time for banking)

3. Non-Goals

Real-time reporting (sub-second latency on fresh data — not needed for batch reports)

Replace the existing accounting query services (they become the materialized view query layer)

Build a data warehouse (materialized views on PostgreSQL first; extraction to ClickHouse or similar is Phase 2)

Implement metadata-driven reporting (each report has a dedicated view)

4. Current State Audit

Reporting queries that currently hit the OLTP directly:

| Report | Query Pattern | Risk |
|--------|---------------|------|
| Trial Balance | Aggregates `amount_lines` by account with date filters | Full table scan on `amount_lines` |
| Balance Sheet | Complex joins across accounts, entries, amount_lines | Heavy join on OLTP |
| Income Statement | Revenue/expense aggregation by date range | Heavy aggregation on OLTP |
| Cash Flow Statement | Multi-pass query over entries with classification | Complex query plan |
| Loan Aging | Per-loan aging computation with payment history | Sequential scan on loans + payments |
| Branch Performance | Multi-table aggregation per branch | Heavy OLTP read load |

The `LedgerQueryService`, `TrialBalanceService`, and other reporting services use `AmountLine.joins(:entry).where(...)` — these queries will degrade as data grows.

5. Requirements

5.1 Must-Have

- Materialized views for the top 5 reporting queries: trial balance, balance sheet, income statement, loan aging snapshot, branch performance
- Each materialized view is refreshed on a schedule (every 15 minutes, or on demand after close of business)
- Application code queries materialized views instead of live tables for reporting endpoints
- Reporting controllers automatically use the materialized view when available, falling back to live queries if the view is stale
- Refresh is non-blocking (`CONCURRENTLY`) to avoid locking the materialized view for reads

5.2 Nice-to-Have

- View refresh is triggered by business events (new entry posted triggers trial balance refresh for that branch only)
- Historical snapshots are preserved (materialized view data is captured to a `report_snapshots` table at month-end for regulatory audit)
- A dedicated read-only PostgreSQL replica for reporting (Phase 2)

6. Proposed Design

6.1 Materialized View Definitions

```ruby
# db/migrate/20260701000001_create_reporting_materialized_views.rb
class CreateReportingMaterializedViews < ActiveRecord::Migration[8.0]
  def up
    # Trial balance materialized view
    execute(<<~SQL)
      CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW reporting_trial_balances AS
      SELECT
        a.id AS account_id,
        a.account_code,
        a.name AS account_name,
        a.account_type,
        a.normal_credit_balance,
        l.id AS ledger_id,
        l.name AS ledger_name,
        COALESCE(
          SUM(CASE WHEN al.amount_type = 0 THEN al.amount_cents ELSE 0 END)
          - SUM(CASE WHEN al.amount_type = 1 THEN al.amount_cents ELSE 0 END),
          0
        ) AS balance_cents,
        COUNT(DISTINCT e.id) AS entry_count,
        MAX(e.posted_at) AS last_activity_at
      FROM accounting_accounts a
      JOIN accounting_ledgers l ON l.id = a.ledger_id
      LEFT JOIN accounting_amount_lines al ON al.account_id = a.id
      LEFT JOIN accounting_entries e ON e.id = al.entry_id AND e.status = 'posted'
      GROUP BY a.id, a.account_code, a.name, a.account_type, a.normal_credit_balance, l.id, l.name
      ORDER BY a.account_code;
    SQL

    # Balance sheet materialized view
    execute(<<~SQL)
      CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW reporting_balance_sheets AS
      SELECT
        COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN a.account_type = 'asset'
          THEN (CASE WHEN al.amount_type = 0 THEN al.amount_cents ELSE -al.amount_cents END)
          ELSE 0 END), 0) AS total_assets_cents,
        COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN a.account_type = 'liability'
          THEN (CASE WHEN al.amount_type = 1 THEN al.amount_cents ELSE -al.amount_cents END)
          ELSE 0 END), 0) AS total_liabilities_cents,
        COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN a.account_type = 'equity'
          THEN (CASE WHEN al.amount_type = 1 THEN al.amount_cents ELSE -al.amount_cents END)
          ELSE 0 END), 0) AS total_equity_cents,
        CURRENT_DATE AS as_of_date
      FROM accounting_accounts a
      JOIN accounting_amount_lines al ON al.account_id = a.id
      JOIN accounting_entries e ON e.id = al.entry_id AND e.status = 'posted';
    SQL

    # Loan aging materialized view
    execute(<<~SQL)
      CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW reporting_loan_agings AS
      SELECT
        l.id AS loan_id,
        l.loan_number,
        m.id AS member_id,
        CONCAT(m.last_name, ', ', m.first_name) AS member_name,
        l.outstanding_principal_cents,
        lp.last_payment_date,
        CASE
          WHEN lp.last_payment_date IS NULL THEN 'current'
          WHEN lp.last_payment_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '30 days' THEN 'current'
          WHEN lp.last_payment_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '60 days' THEN '30_days'
          WHEN lp.last_payment_date >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '90 days' THEN '60_days'
          ELSE '90_plus_days'
        END AS aging_bucket,
        CURRENT_DATE AS as_of_date
      FROM loans l
      JOIN members m ON m.id = l.member_id
      LEFT JOIN (
        SELECT loan_id, MAX(payment_date) AS last_payment_date
        FROM loan_payments
        GROUP BY loan_id
      ) lp ON lp.loan_id = l.id
      WHERE l.status IN ('active', 'disbursed');
    SQL

    # Add unique indexes for concurrent refresh
    execute("CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_reporting_trial_balances ON reporting_trial_balances (account_id)")
    execute("CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_reporting_balance_sheets ON reporting_balance_sheets (as_of_date)")
    execute("CREATE UNIQUE INDEX idx_reporting_loan_agings ON reporting_loan_agings (loan_id)")
  end

  def down
    execute("DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW IF EXISTS reporting_trial_balances")
    execute("DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW IF EXISTS reporting_balance_sheets")
    execute("DROP MATERIALIZED VIEW IF EXISTS reporting_loan_agings")
  end
end
```

6.2 Refresh Job

```ruby
# app/jobs/reporting/refresh_materialized_views_job.rb
module Reporting
  class RefreshMaterializedViewsJob < ApplicationJob
    queue_as :default
    repeating_at "every 15 minutes", timezone: "Asia/Manila"

    def perform
      # CONCURRENTLY requires a unique index on the materialized view
      ActiveRecord::Base.connection.execute("REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY reporting_trial_balances")
      ActiveRecord::Base.connection.execute("REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY reporting_balance_sheets")
      ActiveRecord::Base.connection.execute("REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW CONCURRENTLY reporting_loan_agings")
    end
  end
end
```

6.3 Application Query Layer

```ruby
# app/services/accounting/trial_balance_service.rb (updated excerpt)
class Accounting::TrialBalanceService
  def call(as_of_date: Date.current)
    if use_materialized_view?
      # Query materialized view
      Reporting::TrialBalance.all
    else
      # Fallback to live query
      legacy_trial_balance(as_of_date)
    end
  end

  private

  def use_materialized_view?
    # Use materialized view unless view is older than 30 minutes
    view_age = Reporting::TrialBalance.maximum(:last_activity_at)
    view_age.nil? || view_age > 30.minutes.ago
  end
end
```

